19:28.770 --> 19:31.110
And getting back into the country certainly hasn't been easy.

19:31.550 --> 19:40.670
In terms of leaving the country, we've heard, for example, as well from Athens, the foreign ministry saying that it's working to repatriate about 149 Greek tourists from Israel.

19:40.670 --> 19:44.610
Some of them were due to arrive back late last night into Greece.

19:44.890 --> 19:49.650
But there is indeed much concern about many of the foreign workers in Israel.

19:49.830 --> 19:53.370
I know, for example, Thailand has about 30,000 workers in Israel.

19:53.570 --> 19:58.130
And so governments around the world looking at how they can get their citizens home, if indeed they want to leave Israel.

19:58.690 --> 20:01.830
All right, Katie Silver, always a pleasure to have you on the program.

20:01.990 --> 20:04.230
Our business correspondent there in Singapore.

20:04.230 --> 20:10.830
And we are remaining with this story, and we are now going to speak to our international editor, Jeremy Bowen.

20:11.130 --> 20:16.330
Good morning to you, Jeremy. Now, you have called this a major Middle East crisis.

20:16.810 --> 20:18.790
Can you elaborate that for us, please, if you may?

20:19.970 --> 20:29.310
Well, it's unprecedented that the Palestinian armed group Hamas has been able to break out of Gaza,

20:29.310 --> 20:35.250
which is surrounded by, if you like, a ring of steel of fences, wire fences and concrete,

20:36.110 --> 20:42.650
break out and kill huge numbers of Israelis, including many, many civilians.

20:43.470 --> 20:47.530
That kind of thing is something that Israel hasn't experienced before.

20:48.430 --> 20:58.490
And it's becoming clear that it's a national trauma and plenty of people here compare it to the 9-11 attacks in the United States.

20:58.490 --> 21:04.790
There's even one article in one of the newspapers here saying that if you adjust the death toll for population,

21:04.790 --> 21:09.550
it's the equivalent of the Americans losing more than 20,000 on 9-11.

21:09.850 --> 21:19.030
So it's a big, big event. And the Israeli response, which is going to be, is already very heavy military action,

21:19.070 --> 21:22.570
but I think there'll be a land invasion, too, of Gaza.

21:22.570 --> 21:28.390
Now, that also is something that could have reverberations right across the region.

21:29.050 --> 21:32.330
So we're into really unexplored territory right now.

21:33.230 --> 21:36.670
And Jeremy, you have been in the region, you have been in the area.

21:36.930 --> 21:43.610
Just for our listeners' benefit, can you describe what Gaza Strip looks like and how that area is to Israel?

21:45.590 --> 21:54.810
Gaza is a narrow strip of land along the Mediterranean coast, which is surrounded mostly by Israel,

21:56.390 --> 22:01.530
but with a narrow border which also goes into Egypt.

22:03.190 --> 22:08.910
The Palestinian population of Gaza is around 2.4 million people.

22:08.910 --> 22:16.830
Many of them are descendants of families who lost their homes when Israel was created in 1948,

22:16.830 --> 22:20.730
a time that the Palestinians call the Nakba, the catastrophe.

22:21.890 --> 22:25.290
And it's an area where people are mostly very poor.

22:25.490 --> 22:28.810
They live in very difficult and cramped conditions.

22:29.150 --> 22:31.730
They're mostly not allowed to leave the area.

22:32.290 --> 22:35.690
There are plenty of adults there who've never left.

22:35.690 --> 22:44.110
And so it is a situation which is, life there is very hard and it's highly nationalistic.

22:44.390 --> 22:49.790
And since 2007, it's been controlled by the Palestinian militant group Hamas,

22:50.010 --> 22:53.630
which is an Arabic acronym for the Islamic Resistance Movement.

22:54.330 --> 23:00.770
And you wrote a nice read on our website where you said that Hamas blindsided Israel

23:00.770 --> 23:04.230
with what you called the most serious attack in a generation.

23:04.230 --> 23:09.950
And we're hearing stories of hostages that have been taken, including civilians as well as soldiers.

23:10.590 --> 23:15.790
What sort of challenge does this pose for the government of Mr Netanyahu and the army going forward?

23:17.130 --> 23:23.090
It's the most profound challenge that any Israel government has, I think, faced probably for 50 years

23:23.090 --> 23:25.750
since the 1973 Middle East war.

23:28.310 --> 23:35.930
His political enemies are already blaming him, saying that he took his arf the ball for a variety of reasons.

23:36.990 --> 23:41.030
It's clear that there's been from the Israeli perspective a huge intelligence failure

23:41.030 --> 23:44.490
and they're struggling militarily to assert themselves.

23:44.650 --> 23:46.290
They will succeed in doing that.

23:46.430 --> 23:50.450
I'm pretty certain because Israel has got very powerful armed forces.

23:50.450 --> 23:59.310
I think the big question, and this is probably an equal challenge for the Israelis,

24:00.010 --> 24:01.910
is what happens after that?

24:04.010 --> 24:07.390
What happens in Gaza on the day that they leave?

24:07.750 --> 24:13.850
Because the Israelis who used to occupy Gaza and finally pulled out in 2005

24:15.230 --> 24:18.090
do not want to get back into a full-scale occupation.

24:18.090 --> 24:24.290
But if they sent in their troops, there's going to have to be some kind of governance of a territory

24:24.290 --> 24:30.750
which is maybe small, but as I said, contains getting on for two and a half million people.

24:31.930 --> 24:36.170
Jeremy Bowen there. Thank you for coming on the programme. He is our international editor.

